article.headline: Feaster's late jumper lifts Charlotte
article.linkText: Sting gain road victory at Washington
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite a little jet lag, Allison Feaster made
an immediate contribution in her first game back with the Charlotte
Sting.

Feaster hit a 17-foot jumper with 1:08 remaining to put
Charlotte ahead and the Sting went on to beat the Washington
Mystics 71-68 on Saturday night.

Feaster missed the Sting's first game and training camp while
she was finishing her season playing in France. She returned to the
United States on Friday.

"It's probably bedtime," Feaster said about the time change.
"I just feel my teammates really welcomed me back. I feel like
I've been playing with them since day one of training camp."

She scored 15 points on 4-of-8 shooting, and was one of five
Charlotte players in double figures. Her late jumper made the score
69-68.

Washington's Chamique Holdsclaw missed a jumper in the lane with
12 seconds left and Charlotte Smith-Taylor, who scored 10 points,
sank two free throws with 8.8 seconds to go for the Sting.

Mystics rookie Alana Beard missed a potential tying 3-pointer in
the final seconds.

It was a mixed debut for Beard, who showed tremendous hustle on
defense forcing two steals and blocking four shots. However, the
former Duke All-American hit just 3-for-10 from the floor to finish
with 10 points.

"She's a great defensive player let's not forget that, but I
think she struggled a little bit offensively," Mystics coach
Michael Adams said. "I don't think we had too many players making
too many shots in the first half anyways."

Tynesha Lewis scored 16 points and Dawn Staley added 12 for the
Sting, who overcame 19 turnovers.

Holdsclaw scored 25 points for Washington, and Tamicha Jackson
added 17.

Adams was also making his WNBA debut. He was one of the NBA's
top 3-point shooters during an 11-year career, but had never been a
head coach before the Mystics hired him in February.

Adams watched his team battle back from a 13-point deficit only
to be outscored 6-0 over the final 1:59.

Tammy Sutton-Brown and Feaster scored 10 of the Sting's final 14
points. Charlotte hit 20 of 23 from the free throw line for the
game, including 10 straight in the final five minutes.

Charlotte's defense held Washington without a basket for the
final five minutes of the first half to take a 29-24 halftime lead.

Lewis capped the first half with a no-look shot over her
shoulder that banked in at the halftime buzzer for two.
